data:
Newtonhill School are continuing with this 1+2 Curriculum Development project as we very much want to raise our school standards in the learning and teaching of modern foreign languages, and to develop the internationalisation of our school community. This is part of our SQUIP this year, and will remain on the plan until 2020 when we hope to have this embedded across the school in line with Scottish and Aberdeenshire initiatives. In our last application, we expressed our need to raise standards of learning and teaching in Spanish in order to put our P7s on a level playing field with all other cluster P7s.  Whist this is improving, it is not quite there yet. We aim to provide high quality learning and teaching experiences for all 350 children at Newtonhill School, across the curriculum.  We would like to bring the Spanish learning and teaching experiences up to the high standard we expect in other curricular areas, and so asked for further staff volunteers to attend the LFEE Level 1 Spanish Immersion Course in Malaga during this year's summer holiday, and encouraged the staff who had successfully completed the Level 1 course to apply for Level 2. We are therefore applying for funding for 8 staff with a view to these staff to starting to or continuing to, at a higher level,:

develop and/or share a range of resources and training/support activities;
present these to staff in our own school and other schools in our cluster network;
lead department and whole school assemblies, including parent assemblies, with Spanish theme or some Spanish content;
work with staff across the authority to share their experiences to inspire and motivate across Aberdeenshire and/or Scotland;
develop existing and create new links with classes in Spain so that learners across our school have experience of an etwinning project or similar, in order to promote global and particularly European citizenship;
work in school and beyond to create manageable, sustainable but high quality short-, medium- and long-term planning of the teaching and learning of foreign languages, developing contexts suitable for all ages across primary school.

Having had some staff attend the high quality immersion course, and seen the impact it has had on them, their classes and those around them, we realise the more staff we can put on that training, the better.  Although some staff have fully embraced the 1+2 initiative, some less confident ones are very much still at the "toe in the water" stage.  The more fully trained staff we have, the better we can support those teachers who do not wish to undertake any further training yet, by putting confident, skilled staff in as stage language leaders to train, support and team-teach with them, as we are about to start doing with our eTwinning projects this term.

We are beginning to adopt a whole school cross-curricular approach to learning and teaching modern foreign languages at Newtonhill.  Getting started on the etwinning website has made it apparent to our staff what opportunities there are to teach languages and ICT together, through use of the twinspace, digital photography and film-making.  We share our learning with our parents and the wider school community through Twitter, and often share our Spanish language learning on our Twitter feed, (@Newtonhill_Sch), including our Spanish of the Week.  Staff who have volunteered to attend the Level 2 immersion course include 3 members of the management team, 1 of whom is 50% class committed, the other 80%.  We feel this is beneficial as it ensures that the embedding of MFL teaching in Newtonhill School is coming from school leaders who are in a position to change and improve school planning, resources, budgeting and provision of Career-Long Professional Learning opportunities to reflect our whole school needs, and to benefit staff who are unable to attend this type of training for whatever reason.

We will continue to run European projects in various classes across the school each year, both through etwinning and in more traditional ways.  As previously mentioned, we are trying to work in line with local and national guidelines to plan and teach Spanish as our L2 in line with local guidelines (currently all classes should now be receiving learning and teaching experiences in the school L2) in order to try and meet national priorities by 2020 of providing the learning and teaching of an L2 to all P1-P7 learners, and a quality learning and teaching experience of an L3 from P5-P7.  We continue to be committed to the development of this mobility project and will do our best to take the entire school community along with us.

Newtonhill School are running this 1+2 Curriculum Development project as we very much want to raise our school standards in the learning and teaching of modern foreign languages, and to develop the internationalisation of our school community.  This is part of our School Improvement Plan this year, and will remain on the plan until 2020 when we hope to have this embedded across the school in line with Scottish and Aberdeenshire initiatives.  In our local authority, primary schools work with their area schools network to allocate languages for P6 and P7 to ensure an even spread of learners with experiences of the modern foreign language they will learn in S1 and 2 at their academy.  Therefore, in our network, because the languages taught in S1 are French and Spanish, half the P6s and 7s should receive French language tuition, and half Spanish.  Newtonhill School must teach and learn Spanish, and we are very keen to do this to a high standard, but none of the staff have any knowledge of Spanish.  We have more than 380 pupils at Newtonhill School, and we aim to provide high quality learning and teaching experiences for all children across the curriculum.  We would like to bring the Spanish learning and teaching experiences up to the high standard we expect in other curricular areas, and so asked for staff volunteers to attend the LFEE Spanish Immersion Course in Malaga during this year's summer holiday.  We are applying for funding for 4 staff with a view to these staff:

sharing and/or developing a range of resources and training/support activities;
presenting these to staff in our own school and other schools in our cluster network;
leading department and whole school assemblies, including parent assemblies, with Spanish theme or some Spanish content;
working with staff across the authority to share their experiences to inspire and motivate across Aberdeenshire and/or Scotland;
develop existing and create new links with classes in Spain so that learners across our school have experience of an etwinning project or similar, in order to promote global and particularly European citizenship;
working in school and beyond to create manageable, sustainable but high quality short-, medium- and long-term planning of the teaching and learning of foreign languages, developing contexts suitable for all ages across primary school.

High quality training and resources are desperately needed.  The immersion course will be a continuation of short upskilling courses in Spanish language, and will come after a year of a "toe in the water" approach to teaching Spanish across the school.  We have already initiated some very small-scale etwinning projects with schools in France and Spain, which has made us appreciate how advanced in foreign language learning similar-aged children are in Europe.   

We are trying to adopt a whole school cross-curricular approach to learning and teaching modern foreign languages at Newtonhill.  Getting started on the etwinning website has made it apparent to our staff what opportunities there are to teach languages and ICT together, through use of the twinspace, digital photography and film-making.  We share our learning with our parents and the wider school community through Twitter, and will go on to incorporate our Spanish language learning on our Twitter feed, starting with the children putting on an example of good pronunciation of our "Spanish of the Week".  Staff who have volunteered to attend the immersion course include 3 members of the management team, 2 of whom are at least 50% class committed.  We feel this is beneficial as it ensures that the embedding of MFL teaching in Newtonhill School is coming from school leaders who are in a position to change and improve school planning, resources, budgeting and provision of Career-Long Professional Learning opportunities to reflect our whole school needs, and to benefit staff who were not free to volunteer to attend the immersion course this summer.

We will continue to run European projects in various classes across the school each year, both through etwinning and in more traditional ways.  As previously mentioned, we are trying to work in line with local and national guidelines to plan and teach Spanish to at least P1-3 this year.  This will be extended over the next 2 or 3 years to include P4-7, again in line with local guidelines in order to try and meet national priorities by 2020 of providing the learning and teaching of an L2 (which of course for us is Spanish) to the whole school, and experiences of other languages to P5-7.  Staff will incorporate their development in learning and teaching Spanish into their yearly Career-Long Professional Learning requirement, and will be supported through this by a series of planned courses and events run in conjunction with Aberdeenshire development officers.  We are committed to the development of this project and will do our best to take the entire school community along with us.
